 ORs of all the non-empty subarrays of arr.\nThe bitwise OR of a subarray is the bitwise OR of each integer in the subarray. The bitwise OR of a subarray of one integer is that integer.\nA subarray is a contiguous non-empty sequence of elements within an array.\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: arr = [0]\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: There is only one possible result: 0.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: arr = [1,1,2]\nOutput: 3\nExplanation: The possible subarrays are [1], [1], [2], [1, 1], [1, 2], [1, 1, 2].\nThese yield the results 1, 1, 2, 1, 3, 3.\nThere are 3 unique values, so the answer is 3.\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: arr = [1,2,4]\nOutput: 6\nExplanation: The possible results are 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, and 7.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= arr.length <= 5 * 104\n0 <= arr[i] <= 109\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def subarrayBitwiseORs(self, arr: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def subarrayBitwiseORs(self, arr: List[int]) -> int:\n        current = set()\n        result = set()\n        \n        for num in arr:\n            # Update the current set with the bitwise OR of num with each element in current\n            current = {num | y for y in current} | {num}\n            # Add all elements in current to the result set\n            result.update(current)\n        \n        return len(result)\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n- We use a set `current` to keep track of all unique bitwise OR results of subarrays ending at the current index.\n- We use another set `result` to store all unique bitwise OR results encountered so far.\n- For each number in the array, we update the `current` set by taking the bitwise OR of the number with each element already in `current`, and also include the number itself.\n- We then add all elements from `current` to `result`.\n- Finally, the size of the `result` set gives us the number of distinct bitwise OR results of all non-empty subarrays.", "estimated_date": 1535846400000}